{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9c839dfe-9a7e-4a92-a8af-417c054b4c7e","content":"`SafeAreaEdges` alone isn't sufficient. You likely need two things:\n\n**1. Set `IgnoreSafeArea` on the layout/view itself:**\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns=\"http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui\"\n             Padding=\"0\">\n    <Grid IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\">\n        <Image Source=\"photo.jpg\"\n               Aspect=\"AspectFill\" />\n    </Grid>\n</ContentPage>\n```\n\n**2. On Android, configure edge-to-edge in `MainActivity.cs`:**\n\n```csharp\nprotected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)\n{\n    base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);\n    Window.SetFlags(WindowManagerFlags.LayoutNoLimits,\n                    WindowManagerFlags.LayoutNoLimits);\n}\n```\n\nThis makes the window draw behind the status bar and navigation bar on Android. On iOS, `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` on the `Grid` handles it.\n\nAlso ensure your page has `Padding=\"0\"` and no `Shell.NavBarIsVisible=\"True\"` adding chrome above your content.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4df4b8c5-2adf-4c24-ab5e-c1f7ff0a9c2c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about making content go edge-to-edge (behind status bar and navigation bar) in a .NET MAUI app targeting .NET 10. They've set `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` on the ContentPage but still see padding around the image.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, to achieve true edge-to-edge display, you need to do more than just set `SafeAreaEdges`. Let me think about what's needed:\n\n1. **`IgnoreSafeArea`** - In .NET MAUI, views have an `IgnoreSafeArea` property that needs to be set to `true` on the layout or image itself.\n\n\n2. **Edge-to-edge on Android** - Starting with .NET 9/.NET 10, Android apps may need to opt into edge-to-edge mode explicitly or handle window insets properly.\n3. **`Padding`** - The ContentPage or its layout might have default padding that's causing the visible spacing.\n\nThe approach differs between platforms—on iOS, `IgnoreSafeArea` is the key setting, but Android's handling of system bars changed in recent .NET MAUI versions and may require additional configuration or platform-specific code. I'm realizing `SafeAreaEdges` isn't actually a standard .NET MAUI property—the user might be confusing it with something else or using a custom implementation. The real approach on iOS is setting `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` on the page itself, while Android requires platform-specific configuration to make the status and navigation bars transparent so content can extend behind them. The key issue is that `IgnoreSafeArea` needs to be set on the root layout container itself, not just the page, and I should verify whether `SafeAreaEdges` is actually a valid MAUI property or if the user might be thinking of a different framework—the actual property in MAUI is `Page.IgnoreSafeArea`.","outputTokens":1567,"requestId":"5029:2657C1:1C507EF:1F767E1:69FA92AA"},"id":"b6333de1-7de0-445a-afaf-64b54ca2b8f1","timestamp":"2026-05-06T01:00:58.245Z","parentId":"b025e072-5d60-47fd-b4a0-b8fade7f6cf4"}
